@manjuraj, maybe something is wrong?

On the stats endpoint, the pool name and server name are being added as keys to the same object that has pre-defined stats in it:

```
$ curl localhost:22222
{
    "service":"nutcracker",
    "source":"i-deadbeef",
    "version":"0.4.1",
    "uptime":4018,
    ...global stats...
    "poolA": {
        "client_eof":221,
        "client_err":0,
        "client_connections":15,
        "fragments":0,
        ...pool stats...
        "serverA": {
            ...server stats...
        }
    }
}
```

As a result I can clobber the higher-level stats by naming a pool `uptime` or naming a server `fragments`:

```
$ curl localhost:22222
{
    "service":"nutcracker",
    "source":"i-deadbeef",
    "version":"0.4.1",
    "uptime": {
        "client_eof":221,
        "client_err":0,
        "client_connections":15,
        ...pool stats...
        "fragments": {
            ...server stats...
        }
    }
    ...global stats...
}
```

As a result, `uptime` and `fragments` are no longer reported.  What I'd really like to do is be able to iterate over a dedicated JSON object or array where I don't need to know ahead of time what the pool or server names are in order to know that they're pool or server stats respectively, Like this:

```
{
    "service":"nutcracker",
    "source":"i-deadbeef",
    ...global stats...
    "pools" {
        "poolA": {
            ...pool stats...
            "forward_error":0,
            "fragments":0,
            "servers": {
                "serverA": {
                    ...server stats...
                    "server_eof":0,
                    "server_err":0,
                },
                "serverB": {
                   ... other server stats...
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

